      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study (coarse, medium, fine) was performed on the non-cannulated 7.5 mm construct model. Stiffness QoI changed by 1.4% and yield force by 1.7% between medium and fine meshes, satisfying the <2% convergence criterion."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals fall below 1e-6 for all load steps; no divergence warnings recorded.",
      "rationale": "Static implicit Newton-Raphson solver residuals were monitored across all load increments. Maximum residual norm did not exceed 8e-7. No convergence failures were recorded across the full displacement-controlled loading protocol."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent analyst review of model setup, boundary conditions, and material assignments confirms correct implementation of ASTM F1717 loading configuration.",
      "rationale": "A second analyst independently reviewed the model setup documentation and spot-checked boundary condition definitions, material property assignments, and load application against the ASTM F1717 standard. No discrepancies were identified."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum elastic-plastic constitutive model with nonlinear geometry captures dominant deformation mechanisms; contact formulation validated against analogous implant studies.",
      "rationale": "The FEA model employs a bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity model for titanium alloy components and a penalty-based contact formulation at the screw-rod interface. Prior literature on pedicle screw FEA supports this model form for capturing bending-dominated failure. Geometric nonlinearity is enabled throughout."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties (elastic modulus, yield strength, tangent modulus) sourced from manufacturer certificates of conformance and published Ti-6Al-4V ELI data; uncertainty bounds quantified.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus (114 GPa), yield strength (827 MPa), and tangent modulus (1.14 GPa) for Ti-6Al-4V ELI were taken from lot-specific certificates of conformance supplemented by ASTM F136 reference values. Coefficient of friction at screw-rod interface (0.23) was measured by tribometer testing on representative surface finishes. Parametric sensitivity analysis confirmed yield strength as the dominant input uncertainty contributor."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 production-representative non-cannulated 7.5 mm constructs tested; dimensional inspection confirms conformance to nominal geometry within manufacturing tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs assembled from production-lot non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws and matched rods were tested. Dimensional inspection of all screws confirmed outer diameter within ±0.05 mm of nominal. Constructs were assembled by trained technicians following manufacturer IFU torque specifications."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading rates and environmental conditions specified in ASTM F1717.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single crosshead displacement rate (5 mm/min) in ambient laboratory conditions per ASTM F1717. Wet or physiological saline conditions and alternative loading rates were not evaluated. This single test condition results in an achieved level of 2, below the required level of 3. This gap is acknowledged and accepted given the standard's primary focus on comparative mechanical performance rather than in vivo simulation fidelity."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model geometry, material properties, and boundary conditions are demonstrably equivalent to the physical test article and test configuration.",
      "rationale": "CAD geometry used in the FEA was derived from the same nominal design files used for manufacture of the tested constructs. Material properties were matched to lot-specific test data. The ASTM F1717 test fixture geometry (35 mm offset, rigid grips) was replicated in the model boundary conditions. Equivalency was confirmed by a formal input-parameter mapping table reviewed by both the modeling team and the testing laboratory."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) satisfy <10% relative difference and E/uval < 1.96 across N=11 specimens.",
      "rationale": "Predicted construct stiffness differed from experimental mean by 4.2% (E/uval = 0.87). Predicted yield force differed by 6.8% (E/uval = 1.31). Predicted force at 40 mm displacement differed by 5.1% (E/uval = 1.04). All three QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria across both laboratories, confirming adequate predictive accuracy."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Selected QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly linked to the clinical risk of construct failure and are the quantities used in the regulatory submission.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness governs load sharing with the anterior column; yield force characterizes onset of permanent deformation; force at 40 mm displacement is the standard ASTM F1717 comparative metric. All three are directly cited in the 510(k) predicate comparison and map to the identified failure modes in the device risk analysis."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
